<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06211054 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06211054 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; OPINION; SURVEY; USSR; PRESIDENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A majority of Americans believe Mikhail Gorbachev is sincere about meaningfulreform in the Soviet Union, but a third of those doubt he will succeed, anAssociated Press poll shows.;    As the Moscow summit meeting betweenPresident Bush and Gorbachev approaches, the American public's belief that theSoviet president wants reform prevails by 60 percent to 18 percent, with morethan a fifth not sure.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  POLL ENDORSES GORBACHEV'S SINCERITY  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Those who consider Gorbachev a genuine reformer and believe he will succeedmake up 25 percent of the 1,007 adults interviewed for the AP poll by the ICRSurvey Research Group of Media, Pa.;    The poll was taken July 19-23, justbefore Gorbachev got the Communist Party he leads to approve a draft platformrejecting the totalitarianism and militant atheism of its past and embracingprivate property and a free market.;    Despite Gorbachev's vaunted personalconfidence, his leadership continues to face a breathtaking array ofchallenges. Right-wing hard-liners, popular reformist rivals, a stodgybureaucracy, a growing foreign debt and public anger at shortages of suchbasics as food and housing top the list.;    In the poll, 28 percent say theirfeelings toward the Soviet Union are generally favorable, 11 percent saygenerally unfavorable and 56 percent say neutral.;    The 28 percent favorablerating is a sharp decline from 41 percent in an earlier AP poll, taken withMedia General Inc. on May 11-20, 1990.;    Results of both polls have a marginof sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  New York  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910729  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  